definitions.description: Response object for the getArtifacts operation

name: dxp_extended_audits
about:
Extended Audits API

About

This API's purpose is to facilitate the search and cross-reference of data in the audit and user activity logs.

This API's operations have two objectives in mind: 

  • getArtifacts: collect all the User, Role, Security Group artifacts in the system and their relations;
  • getAuditLog: to search the audit logs.

Operation getArtifacts

Request parameters

It has no request parameters

Response parameters

Status 200: getArtifactsResponse definition

Usage information

The root node is result, and then artifacts for the User, Role, and Security Group artifacts and relations for the relationships between them:

{
    "result": {
        "artifacts": [...], 
        "relations": {
            "groupsAndRoles": [...], 
            "groupsAndUsers": [...], 
            "rolesAndUsers": [...]
        }
    }
}

Due to equialization between the SAP Edition and the Open Edition of the Neptune DXP, all names were standardized, and that includes the current Security Group.

Security Group was initially Department in Open Edition, so during the normalization process and to ensure backward compatibility, the already existing tables kept making use of "Department" and all the applications and tools display it as "Group" or "Security Group".

This is an example of a Security Group record named "UXP", in the database:

{
    "result": {
        "artifacts": [
            {
                "objectType": "Department",
                "objectKey": "...",
                "name": "UXP",
                "description": "Neptune UX Platform developers",
                "package": null,
                "locked": null,
                "active": null,
                "createdAt": "...",
                "createdBy": "...",
                "updatedAt": "...",
                "changedBy": "..."
            }
        ]
    }
}

This entry is not a 100% 1 to 1 field match for Users, Roles and Security Group entries in the database. The artifacts' structure was normalized to fit all entries in common fields.

The fields' meaning and/or possible values are:

  • objectType: "User", "Role" and "Department";
  • objectKey; the UUID of the object;
  • name: the technical name of the object - for users it's the username;
  • description: the user readable description of the object - for users it's the user's full name;
  • package: null if no package assigned, otherwise it contains the UUID of the package;
  • locked: boolean with the user locked status - null for all other objects;
  • active: 
    • value: boolean with the user active status - null for all other objects;
    • note: it is deemed active if it is within its validity period, and inactive otherwise
  • createdAt/updatedAt: timestamps of the object creation and last update respectively;
  • createdBy/changedBy: username of who created and last updated the object respectively.

Inside of the relations arrays, all of the fields contain the UUID of the respective object. The fields for each relation are:

  • groupsAndRoles: Department and Role;
  • groupsAndUsers: Department and User;
  • rolesAndUsers: Role and User.

Operation getAuditLog

Request parameters

The request parameters is set the body. It uses the getAuditLogRequest definition.

Response parameters

Status 200: getAuditLogResponse definition

Status 400: getAuditLogBadRequest definition 

Usage information - Request

To use this API, the body needs to contain at least a non-empty request. If the request is deemed empty then a 400 response is issued.

A valid parameter is enforced to avoid reading all the audit log entries since the beggining, by accident.

This is the example of one request entry:

{
    "where": [
        {
            "objectType": "Role",
            "objectKey": "New",
            "action": "Save",
            "beginDate": "2023-10-01",
            "endDate": "2023-10-30",
            "changedBy": "paulo",
            "content": "",
        }
    ]
}

This entry will search the audit log for all roles created by the user "paulo" between the dates of 01.10.2023 and 30.10.2023.

If we want to get the same query for users "paulo" and "rosa", then two entries need to be sent in the request:

{
    "where": [
        {
            "objectType": "Role",
            "objectKey": "New",
            "action": "Save",
            "beginDate": "2023-10-01",
            "endDate": "2023-10-30",
            "changedBy": "paulo",
            "content": "",
        },
        {
            "objectType": "Role",
            "objectKey": "New",
            "action": "Save",
            "beginDate": "2023-10-01",
            "endDate": "2023-10-30",
            "changedBy": "rosa",
            "content": "",
        }

    ]
}

Object types

This is a list of object types used in the system:

  • API: Entries on the API Designer;
  • Tile: Entries on the Tile manager;
  • Category: Entries on the Tile Group manager;
  • Launchpad: Entries on the Launchpad manager;
  • User: Entries on the User manager;
  • Role: Entries on the Role manager;
  • Department: Entries on the Security Group manager;
  • ServerScript: Entries on the Script Editor;
  • SystemSettings: Entries related to changes on the system setting.

NOTE: this is a provisory list. An accurate and updated list of the core object types will be supplied.

NOTE: Marketplace add-ons can also write to the Audit Log, but they will not take part of this core list. Each add-on must indicate which Type and Actions it registers to the Audit Log.

Object keys

The object key field can be null, "New" or the UUID of the modified/deleted object.

Actions

The actions are closely related to the object Type and how the application was designed. 

The actions, for the currently listed object types, are "Activity", "Save", and "Delete".

To query for newly created objects set the objectKey field to "New" and the action field to "Save".

The "Activity" action is specific for the "User" object type. It is related to the user activity, which entries reside in a table different from the audit log. The getAuditLog operation merges the user activities into the result by adding the action "Activity" to object type "User". Read more about this in the section dedicated to the response output.

Begin date

First date of the period. If left empty then it looks for entries since the beggining.

End date

End date of the period. If left empty then it looks up to today's date (inclusive).

Changed by

The username of who executed the action

Content

All Audit Log entries refer to the object they modified through the "content" field in the response. The "content" field in the request allows the user to query for entries which content contains the specified string. Which content can exist is dependent on the type of object.

Usage information - Response

The operation will return status 400 if no request parameter is given or is empty of values.

Each response has the following structure:

{
    "result": {
        "audit": [
            {
                "id": "UUID of the audit log entry",
                "objectType": "type of the affected object",
                "objectKey": "key of the affected object",
                "action": "action taken",
                "content": "stringified version of the JSON data of the affected object, as it is after the action is taken"
                "createdAt": "creation timestamp",
                "updatedAt": "update timestamp",
                "changedBy": "username that took the action",
                "objectName": "name of the affected object"
            }
        ]
    }
}

The field "audit" is an array and contains the result sorted by "updatedAt" DESCENDING.

The "content" field can't be described because it depends on the type of object. It is still parseable because it is delivered in the a JSON stringified version.

User activity

The user activity is added to the audit log as a virtual entry. One can look at it as if getting the entries through a view.

For all entries found in the user activity table, an entry is added to the "audit" array in the following format:

{
    "id": `*${user_activity.id}`,
    "objectType": "User",
    "objectKey": `${user_activity.userId}`,
    "action": "Activity",
    "content": `${JSON.stringify(user_activity)}`,
    "createdAt": `${user_activity.createdAt}`,
    "updatedAt": `${user_activity.createdAt}`,
    "changedBy": `${getUsernameOf(user_activity.userId)}`,
    "objectName": `${getNameOf(user_activity.userId)}`
}

NOTE: in the example above, user_activity is supposed to be one instance of the several user activities found.
